 this foundational insight to both examine the considerable, ongoing role that Los Angeles played in the history of Spanish-language cinema and to explore the implications of this transnational dynamic for the study and analysis of Latin American cinema before 1960. The volume editors aim to flesh out the gaps between Hollywood and Latin America, American imperialism and Latin American nationalism in order to produce a more nuanced view of transnational cultural relations in the western hemisphere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHispanic Americans in the motion picture industryzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picture industryzCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures, MexicanzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  acinema, Latin America, Los Angeles, Hollywood, Latino, immigrant, multidirectional, Spanish-language, film, entertainment, Mexico.1 aAvila, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvila, Jacqueline.1 aBesné, Viviana García.1 aGarcia, Desirée J.1 aGarcia, Desirée J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía Besné, Viviana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunckel, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunckel, Colin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHoechtl, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoechtl, Nina.1 aHorak, Jan-Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorak, Jan-Christopher, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJarvinen, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJarvinen, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http: